[Student "S"]
{The 2\S bid is used as a transfer to 3\C.

If you don't use this in your system, just consider this hand; you might decide to incorporate it. So you bid 3\C and everybody passes.

South plays 3\C. West leads the \HJ.

You play dummy's \HQ hopefully, but East plays the \HK.

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 1 : \D = 2 : \C = 1 :: Total = 5

That is one loser too many. The \CQ MIGHT drop . . . but she won't. There are no finesse positions. So you are going to have to establish a winner somewhere to discard dummy's small \S. 

Do you see it? The \H8. Take the \HA. Then play your \C A K. As predicted, the \CQ doesn't fall. Then play a small \H to dummy's \H9. Of course West will take the \H10, but now your \H8 is high.

As soon as you get the lead you play the \H8 and discard dummy's \S2. 

We know, you didn't really play the \HQ on the first trick in the hope that West had underled the \HK (although he certainly might have done so).

The real reason for covering was so you could establish the \H8 by force.

Suppose you had not played the \HQ to trick one. East would have withheld the \HK and you'd have had to take your \HA. Later East would have taken dummy's \HQ with his \HK, then played a small \H through your \H8 to West's \H 10 7.}
[Play "W"]HJ

